'''Norman W. C. Powell''' (born May 25, 1993)<ref name="ucla_bio">{{cite news|title=Norman Powell Biography|work=UCLABruins.com|url=http://www.uclabruins.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=30500&ATCLID=207913792|accessdate=April 25, 2014}}</ref> is an American professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Toronto Raptors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). Playing [[college basketball]] with the [[UCLA Bruins men's basketball|UCLA Bruins]], he was an all-conference player in the [[Pac-12 Conference men's basketball|Pac-12]]. He was selected in the second round of the [[2015 NBA draft]].

Powell was a two-time all-state high school player in California and led his team to a state championship before joining UCLA.  After entering his senior year in 2014–15 as the Bruins' top returning player, he emerged as a team leader and received first-team [[List of All-Pac-12 Conference men's basketball teams|All-Pac-12]] honors. He was drafted by the [[Milwaukee Bucks]], who subsequently traded his draft rights to Toronto.

==Early years==
Powell was born in [[San Diego]], [[California]], to Sharon and Norman Powell Sr.<ref name="ucla_bio" /> He was introduced to basketball by his uncle, Raymond Edwards. Powell decided to attend high school at [[Lincoln High School (San Diego)|Lincoln High]], which had just been rebuilt and lost many athletes.<ref name="painter_0320104">{{cite news|last=Painter|first=Jill|title=UCLA’s Norman Powell a slam dunk in San Diego|date=March 20, 2014|newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News|url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20140320/uclas-norman-powell-a-slam-dunk-in-san-diego|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6P6o9aMWK?url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20140320/uclas-norman-powell-a-slam-dunk-in-san-diego|archivedate=April 25, 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> He helped rebuild their basketball program,<ref name="painter_0320104" /> leading the team to consecutive [[California Interscholastic Federation]] (CIF) San Diego Section 2A championships in 2009 and 2010.  The team also captured the 2010 CIF Division II Boys' State Championship, with Powell scoring 24 [[point (basketball)|points]] in a 74–59 win over [[Saint Francis High School (Mountain View)|Mountain View St. Francis]].  He finished his junior season averaging 19.7 points, 4.9 [[rebound (basketball)|rebounds]], and 2.7 [[steal (basketball)|steals]], and earned first-team all-state as well as Western League Most Valuable Player (MVP) honors.<ref name="ucla_bio" /><ref name="maffei_01132014">{{cite news|last=Maffei|first=John|title=Lincoln's Powell enjoying ride at UCLA|date=January 13, 2014|newspaper=U-T San Diego|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2014/Jan/13/alumni-report-powell/|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6P6uK7viY?url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2014/Jan/13/alumni-report-powell/|archivedate=April 26, 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

In his senior year, he was again first-team all-state and league MVP, and averaged 20.4 points, 3.8 rebounds, 2.4 steals. Lincoln was 32–2 and won the league title with a 12–0 record. They were ranked No. 3 in California and No. 15 nationally, but were defeated 74–69 by Summit in the state semifinals.<ref name="ucla_bio" /> He finished his high school career winning the San Diego County All Star Game Dunk Contest.<ref>{{cite news|last=Angulo|first=Blair|title=In transition with Norman Powell|date=April 27, 2011|work=ESPN.com|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/los-angeles/ucla/post/_/id/5787/in-transition-with-norman-powell|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PBrXWYKT?url=http://espn.go.com/blog/los-angeles/ucla/post/_/id/5787/in-transition-with-norman-powell|archivedate=April 29, 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

Considered a four-star recruit by [[ESPN.com]], Powell was listed as the No. 15 shooting guard and the No. 52 player in the nation in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/basketball/recruiting/player/_/id/102170/norman-powell|title=Norman Powell Recruiting Profile|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=April 29, 2014}}</ref> Powell chose to play [[college basketball]] for [[UCLA Bruins men's basketball|UCLA]] over [[San Diego State Aztecs men's basketball|San Diego State]], [[Arizona Wildcats men's basketball|Arizona]] and [[Oregon Ducks men's basketball|Oregon]].<ref name="maffei_01132014" />

==College career==
In his first year at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA), he was the only true freshman to play significant minutes in [[2011–12 UCLA Bruins men's basketball team|2011–12]], when he averaged 17.8 minutes and contributed 4.6 points and 2.2 rebounds in 33 games, joining Tyler Lamb and [[Lazeric Jones]] as the only Bruins to play in every game that season.<ref>{{cite book|title=2013–14 UCLA Bruins Men's Basketball Media Guide|page=60|publisher=UCLA Athletics|url=http://issuu.com/uclabruins/docs/full_guide_8ad1830246e372/60?e=1901135/5335034|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6P7B10zy5?url=http://issuu.com/uclabruins/docs/full_guide_8ad1830246e372/60?e=1901135/5335034|archivedate=April 26, 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> While he excelled as a driving guard in high school, his role transformed at UCLA, taking less than one-fourth of his shots around the rim and close to half from outside on [[three-point field goal|three-point attempts]],<ref name="wang_03102015">{{cite news|last=Wang|first=Jack|title=Norman Powell is thankful for his UCLA career, both the good and the bad|date=March 10, 2015|newspaper=Daily News|url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20150310/norman-powell-is-thankful-for-his-ucla-career-both-the-good-and-the-bad|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WxOtoVgL?url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20150310/norman-powell-is-thankful-for-his-ucla-career-both-the-good-and-the-bad|archivedate=March 11, 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref> connecting on 38.5% over the last 18 games.<ref name="ucla_bio" />

[[File:Norman Powell with Steve Alford (2) (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Powell as a junior in 2014]]
Powell averaged 6.1 points in 22.1 minutes in [[2012–13 UCLA Bruins men's basketball team|2012–13]], making nine starts while playing all 35 games.<ref name="ucla_bio" /> He began the season as a starter, but was later moved to the bench. His minutes declined from an average of 28.4 in the first seven games to 19 the following 26 games. After replacing injured starter [[Jordan Adams]], Powell's minutes increased to 37 per game.<ref name="yoon_04022013" /> He considered transferring to San Diego State after the season,<ref name="katje_03222014" /> but decided to stay primarily because UCLA coach [[Ben Howland]] was fired.<ref name="yoon_04022013" /> Powell credited Howland for his development on defense, but he stated that "there were a lot of things going on that weren’t fair for me" and "I definitely wanted to see a change."<ref name="wang_03102015" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Wang|first=Jack|title=Norman Powell talks about decision to stay at UCLA|date=May 22, 2013|work=insidesocal.com|url=http://www.insidesocal.com/ucla/2013/05/22/norman-powell-talks-about-decision-to-stay-at-ucla/|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WxQwpmK6?url=http://www.insidesocal.com/ucla/2013/05/22/norman-powell-talks-about-decision-to-stay-at-ucla/|archivedate=March 11, 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref> The Bruins hired [[Steve Alford]] as their new coach.<ref name="yoon_04022013">{{cite news|last=Yoon|first=Peter|title=Norman Powell staying after Howland firing|date=April 2, 2013|work=ESPN.com|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/los-angeles/ucla/post/_/id/13723/norman-powell-staying-after-howland-firing|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6P6wy90vT?url=http://espn.go.com/blog/los-angeles/ucla/post/_/id/13723/norman-powell-staying-after-howland-firing|archivedate=April 26, 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

In [[2013–14 UCLA Bruins men's basketball team|2013–14]], Powell started all 37 games and was third on the team in scoring (11.4).<ref name="ucla_bio" /> Under Alford, he became an offensive threat and a staunch defender.<ref name="wang_03102015" /> He was more aggressive taking the ball to the basket, and dunked more than he could in Howland's system.<ref name="painter_0320104" /><ref name="krasovic_03202014" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Chris|title=Norman Powell, Tony Parker can lift UCLA up a notch when they're on|date=March 19, 2014|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2014/mar/19/sports/la-sp-ucla-powell-parker-20140320|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6P7Dddxfn?url=http://articles.latimes.com/2014/mar/19/sports/la-sp-ucla-powell-parker-20140320|archivedate=April 26, 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> The team's best on-ball defender, Powell was routinely assigned the opponent's best offensive player and earned honorable mention for the [[Pac-12 Conference]] All-Defensive Team.<ref name="katje_03222014">{{cite news|last=Kartje|first=Ryan|title=Defensive stopper Norman Powell gets UCLA going|date=March 22, 2014|newspaper=Orange County Register|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/powell-606644-ucla-best.html|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6P6zMQkOF?url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/powell-606644-ucla-best.html|archivedate=April 26, 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Wang|first=Jack|title=Kyle Anderson, Jordan Adams lead UCLA’s All-Pac-12 awards|date=March 10, 2014|work=insidesocal.com|url=http://www.insidesocal.com/ucla/2014/03/10/kyle-anderson-jordan-adams-lead-uclas-all-pac-12-awards/|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6P6zuSr9S?url=http://www.insidesocal.com/ucla/2014/03/10/kyle-anderson-jordan-adams-lead-uclas-all-pac-12-awards/|archivedate=April 26, 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> UCLA opened the [[2014 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|2014 NCAA Tournament]] in San Diego, enabling him to play in his hometown for the first time since high school.<ref name="krasovic_03202014">{{cite news|last=Krasovic|first=Tom|title=Unleashing Powell, UCLA's Alford ignited Bruins|date=March 20, 2014|newspaper=U-T San Diego|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2014/mar/20/norman-powell-steve-alford-ucla-howland-tulsa/all/?print|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6P7CdN7z2?url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2014/mar/20/norman-powell-steve-alford-ucla-howland-tulsa/all/?print|archivedate=April 26, 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> UCLA advanced to the Sweet 16, and Powell averaged 13.0 points and 2.7 rebounds in three tournament contests. After the season, he considered playing professionally in the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA), and requested an evaluation of his prospects for the upcoming [[2014 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wang|first=Jack|title=Report: Jordan Adams, Norman Powell file paperwork for NBA draft status|date=April 13, 2014|work=insidesocal.com|url=http://www.insidesocal.com/ucla/tag/norman-powell/|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6P6tSmQ5y?url=http://www.insidesocal.com/ucla/tag/norman-powell/|archivedate=April 26, 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Allen|first=Percy|title=Jordan Adams stays, Byron Wesley leaves|date=April 17, 2014|newspaper=The Seattle Times|url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/huskymensbasketball/2014/04/17/jordan-adams-stays-byron-wesley-leaves/|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6P6tcZ99O?url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/huskymensbasketball/2014/04/17/jordan-adams-stays-byron-wesley-leaves/|archivedate=April 26, 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref>

[[File:Norman Powell and Malik Marquetti (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Powell against [[USC Trojans men's basketball|USC]] in 2015]]
Informed that he was unlikely to be drafted,<ref>{{cite news|last=Plaschke|first=Bill|title=UCLA's Norman Powell puts in four years of consistently hard work|date=March 12, 2015|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/ucla/la-sp-ucla-usc-plaschke-20150313-column.html|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Wzi2mfue?url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/ucla/la-sp-ucla-usc-plaschke-20150313-column.html|archivedate=March 13, 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref> Powell decided to return for his senior year, and became UCLA's top returning player and scorer for [[2014–15 UCLA Bruins men's basketball team|2014–15]] after underclassmen Adams, [[Kyle Anderson (basketball)|Kyle Anderson]] and [[Zach LaVine]] each [[NBA draft declaration|declared for the NBA draft]], while seniors [[Travis Wear|Travis]] and [[David Wear]] graduated.<ref>{{cite news|last=Borzello|first=Jeff|title=CBS Sports Classic capsule: UCLA|date=May 6, 2014|work=CBSSports.com|url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegebasketball/eye-on-college-basketball/24552940/cbs-sports-classic-capsule-ucla|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PPDta3Aq?url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegebasketball/eye-on-college-basketball/24552940/cbs-sports-classic-capsule-ucla|archivedate=May 8, 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Wang|first=Jack|title=UCLA leading scorer Jordan Adams changes course, declares for NBA draft|date=April 26, 2014|newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News|url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20140426/ucla-leading-scorer-jordan-adams-changes-course-declares-for-nba-draft|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PPE2MvCv?url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20140426/ucla-leading-scorer-jordan-adams-changes-course-declares-for-nba-draft|archivedate=May 8, 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> During the offseason, Powell worked to improve his [[Jump shot (basketball)|jump shot]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wang|first=Jack|title=UCLA basketball relying on Norman Powell after tumultuous offseason|date=October 23, 2014|newspaper=Los Angeles Daily News|url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20141023/ucla-basketball-relying-on-norman-powell-after-tumultuous-offseason|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6TcamibEW?url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20141023/ucla-basketball-relying-on-norman-powell-after-tumultuous-offseason|archivedate=October 26, 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> As the season progressed, he grew to be a leader of the team, and increasingly took on more of the offensive load.<ref name="helfan_03022015">{{cite news|last=Helfand|first=Zach|title=Norman Powell is named Pac-12's player of the week for the third time|date=March 2, 2015|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/ucla/uclanow/la-sp-ucla-norman-powell-pac-12-player-week-20150302-story.html|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WjvEp5rD?url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/ucla/uclanow/la-sp-ucla-norman-powell-pac-12-player-week-20150302-story.html|archivedate=March 2, 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Helfand|first=Zach|title=UCLA wakes up in time to beat Washington State, 72-67|date=March 1, 2015|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/ucla/la-sp-ucla-washington-state-20150302-story.html|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WjvLN0XF?url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/ucla/la-sp-ucla-washington-state-20150302-story.html|archivedate=March 3, 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref> Although freshman teammate [[Kevon Looney]] was seen as a potential [[NBA lottery pick]], Powell became the Bruins' most consistent performer.<ref name="wang_03102015" /> On March 1, 2015, Powell scored a career-high 28 points in a 72–67 win over [[Washington State Cougars men's basketball|Washington State]].<ref name="kartje_03012015">{{cite news|last=Kartje|first=Ryan|title=UCLA wakes up in time to defeat Washington State|date=March 1, 2015|newspaper=Orange County Register|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/ucla-652756-game-powell.html|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WjvZq4N7?url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/ucla-652756-game-powell.html|archivedate=March 3, 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref> He averaged 26 points and 5.5 rebounds in two games that week, and was honored with his conference-high third Pac-12 Player of the Week for the season.<ref name="wang_03102015" /><ref name="helfan_03022015" /> The Bruins went 2–0, helping them secure an eventual No.4 seed and first-round bye in the [[2015 Pac-12 Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|2015 Pac-12 Tournament]], and maintaining their hopes of receiving a bid to the NCAA Tournament.<ref name="kartje_03012015" /><ref>{{cite news|title=UCLA grinds out 72-67 victory over Washington State|date=March 1, 2015|work=ESPN.com|agency=Associated Press|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=400593338|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WjwIuPoh?url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=400593338|archivedate=March 3, 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref> At season's end, Powell was voted first-team [[List of All-Pac-12 Conference men's basketball teams|All-Pac-12]], and again received honorable mention for the All-Defensive Team.<ref>{{cite press release|title=2014-15 Pac-12 Conference Men's Basketball Honors|date=March 9, 2015|publisher=Pac-12|url=http://pac-12.com/article/2015/03/09/2014-15-pac-12-conference-mens-basketball-honors|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6WuCA8C5K?url=http://pac-12.com/article/2015/03/09/2014-15-pac-12-conference-mens-basketball-honors|archivedate=March 9, 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref> He was also named first-team all-district by the [[United States Basketball Writers Association]] (USBWA),<ref name="wang_03102015" /> and second-team all-district by the [[National Association of Basketball Coaches]] (NABC).<ref>{{cite press release|title=National Association of Basketball Coaches Announces 2014-15 Division I All-District Teams and UPS All-District Coaches|date=March 27, 2015|publisher=National Association of Basketball Coaches|url=http://static.psbin.com/w/9/2qxdhr73x7aqb1/2014-15_NABC_Division_I_All-District_Teams_and_Coaches-2.pdf|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6XTS4w79H?url=http://static.psbin.com/w/9/2qxdhr73x7aqb1/2014-15_NABC_Division_I_All-District_Teams_and_Coaches-2.pdf|archivedate=April 1, 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref> He finished as the team leader in scoring with 16.4 points per game, the sixth highest in the conference.<ref name="ucla_bio" />

==Professional career==

===Toronto Raptors (2015–present)===
====Rookie season (2015–2016)====
On June 25, 2015, Powell was selected with the 46th overall pick in the [[2015 NBA draft]] by the [[Milwaukee Bucks]]. His draft rights, along with a 2017 first-round draft pick, were subsequently traded to the [[Toronto Raptors]] for [[Greivis Vásquez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/press-releases/wright-powell-062515|title=Raptors Tab Wright With 20th Pick, Acquire Future First-Round Pick & Rights To Norman Powell From Bucks|date=June 26, 2015|work=NBA.com|accessdate=June 26, 2015}}</ref> After signing with Toronto on July 15,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/press-releases/powell-071515|title=Raptors Sign Norman Powell|date=July 15, 2015|work=NBA.com|accessdate=July 15, 2015}}</ref> he played with the Raptors in the [[2015 NBA Summer League]] in Las Vegas, where he was the only rookie to be named to the All-NBA Summer League First Team.<ref>{{cite news|last=Asano|first=Naoko|title=Raptors rookie Powell could be ‘steal of the draft’|date=October 2, 2015|website=sportsnet.ca|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/basketball/nba/raptors-rookie-powell-could-be-steal-of-the-draft/|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6db5JsaA0?url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/basketball/nba/raptors-rookie-powell-could-be-steal-of-the-draft/|archivedate=December 7, 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Spurs forward Kyle Anderson named Summer League MVP|date=July 19, 2015|work=SI.com|url=https://www.si.com/nba/2015/07/19/nba-summer-league-mvp-kyle-anderson-spurs|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6a9c2ACKV?url=http://www.si.com/nba/2015/07/19/nba-summer-league-mvp-kyle-anderson-spurs|archivedate=July 20, 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref> Powell received playing time early in [[2015–16 Toronto Raptors season|2015–16]] due to injuries to [[Terrence Ross]] and [[DeMarre Carroll]].<ref>{{cite news|last=MacKenzie|first=Holly|title=Q&A With Norman Powell|date=November 19, 2015|website=Raptors.com|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/holly-blog/powell-111915|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6dcVntEbV?url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/holly-blog/powell-111915|archivedate=December 8, 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref> He later received multiple assignments to [[Raptors 905]], Toronto's [[NBA Development League|D-League]] affiliate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dleague.nba.com/news/assignments/|title=2015-16 NBA Assignments|work=NBA.com|accessdate=December 29, 2015}}</ref>

With Carroll out after knee surgery and [[James Johnson (basketball, born 1987)|James Johnson]] sidelined with a sprained ankle, Powell made his first NBA start on February 2, 2016, going scoreless with two steals in 15 minutes in a 104–97 win over the [[Phoenix Suns]].<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Leary|first=Chris|title=Raptors start next streak with win over Suns|date=February 2, 2016|newspaper=Toronto Star|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/raptors/2016/02/02/raptors-start-next-streak-with-win-over-suns.html|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6f2LPRPHD?url=http://www.thestar.com/sports/raptors/2016/02/02/raptors-start-next-streak-with-win-over-suns.html|archivedate=February 4, 2016|deadurl=no}}</ref> On March 15, he made his eighth career start and scored a then season-high 17 points in a 107–89 win over the [[Milwaukee Bucks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160315/TORMIL/gameinfo.html|title=Lowry scores 25 points to lead Raptors past Bucks, 107-89|work=NBA.com|date=March 15, 2016|accessdate=March 15, 2016}}</ref> He topped that mark on March 28, scoring 18 points in a 119–100 loss to the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160328/OKCTOR/gameinfo.html|title=Westbrook's 16th triple-double leads Thunder to 8th in a row|work=NBA.com|date=March 28, 2016|accessdate=March 29, 2016}}</ref> Two days later, he scored 10 points in a 105–97 win over the Atlanta Hawks, helping the Raptors record a 50-win season for the first time in franchise history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160330/ATLTOR/gameinfo.html|title=Raptors beat Hawks 105-97 to notch first 50-win season|work=NBA.com|date=March 30, 2016|accessdate=March 31, 2016}}</ref> On April 8, with All-Stars [[DeMar DeRozan]] and [[Kyle Lowry]] resting, Powell set a new season high with 27 points in a 111–98 win over the [[Indiana Pacers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160408/INDTOR/gameinfo.html|title=Raptors keep Pacers waiting for playoffs with 111-98 win|work=NBA.com|date=April 8, 2016|accessdate=April 9, 2016}}</ref> In the Raptors' regular-season finale, Powell topped that mark again with 30 points in a 103–96 win over the [[Brooklyn Nets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160413/TORBKN/gameinfo.html|title=Raptors rest starters, beat Nets 103-96 in playoff tuneup|work=NBA.com|date=April 13, 2016|accessdate=April 13, 2016}}</ref> After averaging an [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]]-leading 15.3 points per game in April, he was named the conference's [[NBA Rookie of the Month Award|NBA Rookie of the Month]].<ref>{{cite press release|date=April 15, 2016|url=http://www.nba.com/2016/news/04/15/raptors-norman-powell-and-wolves-karl-anthony-towns-rookies-of-month-for-april/|title=Powell, Towns named Kia Rookie|publisher=NBA|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6goGMsBDu?url=http://www.nba.com/2016/news/04/15/raptors-norman-powell-and-wolves-karl-anthony-towns-rookies-of-month-for-april/|archivedate=April 16, 2016|deadurl=no}}</ref>

====Recent years (2016–present)====
Powell played sparingly for the Raptors over the first half of the [[2016–17 Toronto Raptors season|2016–17 season]]. With [[DeMarre Carroll]] sitting out back-to-back games early on in the season, Powell received a number of starting assignments. He would rise to the occasion every time he got an opportunity, only to go missing in action for a handful of games before his services were needed again.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ganter|first=Mike|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/sports/nba/toronto-raptors-cant-find-norman-powell-many-minutes-but-every-time-he-sees-the-court-he-delivers|title=Toronto Raptors can’t find Norman Powell many minutes — but every time he sees the court, he delivers|work=NationalPost.com|date=December 12, 2016|accessdate=February 7, 2017}}</ref> On December 20, 2016, Powell scored a season-high 21 off the bench in a 116–104 win over the [[Brooklyn Nets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899862|title=Lowry, Powell lead Raptors to 116-104 win over Nets|work=ESPN.com|date=December 20, 2016|accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref> He had three more 21-point games over the next three months.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/p/powelno01/gamelog/2017/|title=Norman Powell 2016-17 Game Log|work=Basketball-Reference.com|accessdate=March 4, 2017}}</ref> On April 24, 2017, in Game 5 of the Raptors' first-round playoff series against the [[Milwaukee Bucks]], Powell scored a playoff career-high 25 points to help the Raptors take a 3–2 series lead with a 118–93 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400950415|title=Powell scores 25 as Raptors beat Bucks 118-93 in Game 5|work=ESPN.com|date=April 24, 2017|accessdate=April 25, 2017}}</ref>

On October 8, 2017, Powell signed a four-year, $42 million contract extension with the Raptors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/press-release/raptors-extend-norm-powell|title=Raptors Sign Powell To Contract Extension|work=NBA.com|date=October 8, 2017|accessdate=October 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Wojnarowski>{{cite web|last=Wojnarowski|first=Adrian|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/20924693/toronto-raptors-norman-powell-agree-four-year-42-million-extension|title=Norman Powell reaches four-year extension with Raptors|work=ESPN.com|date=October 5, 2017|accessdate=October 8, 2017}}</ref> The deal, which started with the 2018–19 season, included a player option on the fourth year.<ref name="Wojnarowski" />

On November 5, 2018, against the [[Utah Jazz]], Powell partially dislocated his left shoulder joint, and was ruled out indefinitely.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors lose Powell for ‘weeks’ with dislocated left shoulder|date=November 7, 2018|newspaper=The Toronto Star|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/raptors/2018/11/07/raptors-lose-powell-for-weeks-with-dislocated-left-shoulder.html|accessdate=November 28, 2018}}</ref> He returned to action on December 19 against the [[Indiana Pacers]] after missing 21 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071140|title=VanVleet hits go-ahead 3-pointer, Raptors beat Pacers 99-96|work=ESPN.com|date=December 19, 2018|accessdate=December 19, 2018|quote=Forward Norman Powell returned after a 21-game absence caused by a left shoulder injury.}}</ref> On January 6, 2019, he scored a season-high 23 points in a 121–105 win over the Pacers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071265|title=Powell scores-season-high 23, Raptors beat Pacers 121-105|work=ESPN.com|date=January 6, 2019|accessdate=January 6, 2019}}</ref> On March 22, he had a career-high 11 rebounds in a 116–109 loss to the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071756|title=George scores 28 as Thunder beat Raptors 116-109|work=ESPN.com|date=March 22, 2019|accessdate=March 22, 2019}}</ref> On April 7, he matched his season high with 23 points in a 117–109 overtime win over the [[Miami Heat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071868|title=Heat, needing win, blame ref's inbounds whistle|work=ESPN.com|date=April 7, 2019|accessdate=April 8, 2019}}</ref> Powell won his first championship when the Raptors defeated the [[2018–19 Golden State Warriors season|Golden State Warriors]] in the [[2019 NBA Finals]] in six games.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/13/sports/warriors-raptors.html|title=How the Raptors Won Their First N.B.A. Championship|authorlink=Marc Stein (reporter)|first=Marc|last=Stein|date=June 13, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=June 14, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

